tühjad_terminid.english:
“Blameless” inventory
(See pages xvi and xxxvi of the ACA BRB.)

Childhood neglect
Neglect can involve denial of food, safety and nutrition in childhood. 
Covert neglect can involve favoritism of one sibling over another. There is also neglect in hatefulness, comparing one child with another, or withholding praise. Perfectionism in which a child can never reach a parent’s idea of behavior or performance is covert neglect. 
(See pages 27-34 of ACA BRB.)

Childhood trauma
(See index of ACA BRB.) 
Childhood trauma can involve physical abuse such as hitting, slapping, sexual abuse or battering a child. Or it can be verbal abuse such as threats of hitting or cursing, shaming comments, comparing, chronic hatefulness. 
Childhood trauma can also involve denial of food, safety, and proper nutrition without physical or verbal abuse involved. 
(See pages 27-30 of ACA BRB.)

Claim (to) 
(See page xx of the ACA BRB: “… needed their own claim….”)
Clean (to – the wreckage of the past)
Clear (to – up the wreckage of the past)

Codependence

Critical parent

Critical survival parent 
This is a part of ourselves that tells us we may be making a mistake. Since the critical survival parent may have helped us to stay alive, it is critical (necessary) to our survival. 
(See “To the Beginner in All of Us” trifold and page 121 of The Laundry Lists Workbook.)

Disease of family addiction 
(See disease model on page xxvi of the ACA BRB.)

False self
(See index of the ACA BRB for examples of this term.)

Family roles
(See pages 97 and 98 of the ACA BRB.)

Fix (to – another) 
To touch or hug the person is known as “fixing”.

Hit (experience a) (such as taking a dosage of drugs). 
You can also get a “hit” or become intoxicated from inside drugs such as fear, excitement, and pain. Fear, excitement, and pain are derived from inside drugs connected to adrenalin, endorphins, or melatonin. 
(See pages 16, 23, 69, or 87 of the ACA BRB. Also see
Hope for Adult Children of Alcoholics

Identity Paper
(See chapters 6 and 10 of the ACA BRB.)

Inner Drugs
(See pages 16, 23, and 69 in the ACA BRB.)

Internalize 
 (See page 22 of the ACA BRB.)
Laundry List (14 traits of an adult child of an alcoholic/dysfunctional family)

Loving parent
(See chapter 8 in the ACA BRB.)

Para-alcoholism 
(See page 335 in the ACA BRB.)

People-pleaser or approval seeker
Trait 2 of The Laundry List. We became approval seekers and lost our identity in the process

Relapse
(This can be relapse with alcohol/drugs. Or you can relapse by returning to childhood roles or using the Laundry List Traits to remain stuck in addiction or self-harming behavior/ relationships.)

Relate 
(See chapter 3 of the ACA BRB: My Parents Did Not Drink But I Can Relate.)

Reparenting
Reparenting ourselves can mean many things… (See page 299 of the ACA BRB.) 
By reparenting ourselves, we can believe… (See page 301 of the ACA BRB.)

Rescuer
(See index in ACA BRB for examples.)

Roles that children take on in the alcoholic or dysfunctional home: 
- family hero child (usually the oldest child who is perfectionistic) 
- lost child (usually shy or invisible child) 
- black sheep child (usually the angry or trouble-making child) 
- mascot child (usually the youngest child who uses humor for attention)

Troubled (family) 
(See page xix of the ACA BRB: “troubled family systems”.)

täidetud_terminid.estonian:
Täiskasvanud lapse defintsioon: vaata ATLi sõpruskonna teksti (suure punase raamatu) lehekülgi 3 ja 4. Vaata samuti toimetaja märkust leheküljel VII.

 Täiskasvanud lapse kontseptsioon pärit Alateenist kes alustasid Hope for Adult children of Alcoholics koosolekutega. Meie sõpruskonna algsed liikmed, kes olid üle 18 a, olid täiskasvanud; aga olid kasvanud lastena üles alkohoolsetes kodudes. Täiskasvanud laps tähendab samuti et kui konfronteeritakse, me läheme tagasi meie lapsepõlve tasemele (Allikas: ACA history- an interview with Tony A 1992).

Inglise keelse väljaande koostaja märkus: Enam kui dekaad on möödunud ajast kui tehti intervjuu ühe meie esmastest rajajatest Tony A-ga sõpruskonna teemal mida ta aitas rajada Alateeni liikmetega aastatel 1977-1978.selle raamatu jaoks kasutame me Tony sõnu kui alust et defineerida täiskasvanud lapse isiksust. Täiskasvanud laps on keegi kes vastab täiskasvanu olukordadele eneses kahtlemise, enese süüdistuse või end valesti või alaväärsena tundes- kõik õpituna lapsepõlvest. Ilma abita me alateadlikult toimime lapsepõlves õpitud ebaeffektiivsete mõtete ja kohtumõistmistega. Tagasiminek võib olla õrn aga see on seal saboteerides meie otsuseid ja suhteid.

täidetud_terminid.english:
Addicted to excitement
Trait 8 of The Laundry List. Examples: gossip, dramatic scenes, pending financial failure, or failing health are often the turmoil that adult children create in their lives to fee connected to reality (page 16). Also see page 23.
täidetud_terminid.estonian:
Sõltumine põnevusest
Mustapesu nimekirja 8.tunnus. 
Näited tagarääkimine, dramaatilised stseenid, kestev finantsiline läbikukkumine või terviseprobleemid on sageli raskus  mida täiskasvanud lapsed enda elus loovad et tunda end reaalsusega ühendatud lk 16. Vt ka lk 22.

täidetud_terminid.english: Addictions: switching addictions or substituting addiction (replacing one addiction for another). Addictions can include food, sex, work, gambling, alcohol/drugs.
täidetud_terminid.estonian: Sõltuvused: sõltuvused vahetamine või  ....sõltuvuse ühe sõltuvuse asendamise teistega. Sõltuvuse võivad sisaldada toitu, seksi, tööd, mängurlust, alkoholi/uiimastid.
